{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_function_194prwpx2ry9_2","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Human Design Profile — The 12 Profiles and 6 Lines Explained - Human Design Hub\nURL: https://humandesignhub.app/en/library/profile-overview\nPublished: 2026-02-20T05:20:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n| Line | Name | Core Theme |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Line 1 | Investigator | Foundation, research, security through knowledge |\n| Line 2 | Hermit | Natural talent, withdrawal, the call from others |\n| Line 3 | Martyr | Trial and error, experiential learning, bonds made and broken |\n| Line 4 | Opportunist | Network, community, influence through relationships |\n| Line 5 | Heretic | Universalizing, projection field, practical solutions |\n| Line 6 | Role Model | Three life phases, observation, embodied wisdom |\n[...]\nLine 6— The Role Model lives in three distinct phases. In the first phase (roughly birth to early 30s), they live much like a Line 3, gathering experience and learning what works. In the second phase (30s–50s), they pull back to observe from a higher vantage point. In the third phase, they step back into the world as a genuine role model, embodying the wisdom they have accumulated.\n[...]\n| Profile | Nickname | Life Theme |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1/3 | Investigating Martyr | Must build a solid knowledge base, then test it relentlessly through real-world experience. Life is a research project that never ends. |\n[...]\n| 1/4 | Investigating Opportunist | Deep foundation-building feeds directly into a close-knit network. Knowledge is meant to be shared with people who know and trust you. |\n[...]\n| 2/4 | Hermit Opportunist | Natural talent is discovered in solitude but reaches its fullness through community. The right community calls out gifts the 2/4 didn't know they had. |\n[...]\n| 2/5 | Hermit Heretic | Natural ability projected onto a mass scale. The 2/5 is often seen as a practical solver of collective problems. Alone time is essential to protect against projection overwhelm. |\n[...]\n| 3/\n[...]\n— and is often seen as a savior figure in the\n[...]\n| 3/6 | Experiential Role Model | The deepest trial-and-error Profile, eventually transforming into a living example. The three-phase arc of Line 6 is especially pronounced here: experiment, observe, embody. |\n[...]\n| 4/6 | Network Role Model | Influence through\n[...]\ncommunity, ultimately growing into a\n[...]\n| 5/1 | Heretical Investigator | Extraordinary reach and projection backed by genuinely deep knowledge. The 5/1 can be trusted to deliver because the research is always there. |\n[...]\n| 5/2 | Heretical Hermit |\n[...]\nmeets natural talent. The 5/2 is called by the world to\n[...]\nown yet.\n[...]\n| 6/2 | Role Model Hermit | Three life phases enriched by natural gifts that emerge in solitude. In the final phase, the 6/2 becomes a role model whose talents speak for themselves. |\n[...]\n| 6/3 | Role Model Martyr | Three life phases built on a foundation of rich experiential learning. The mistakes of the first phase become the wisdom of the third. |\n\n---\n\nTitle: HUMAN DESIGN: The 6 Profile Lines Explained // by Sarah Wilder | SARAHWILDER.CO\nURL: https://wildertalismans.com/blogs/human-design/the-6-profile-lines-explained\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nIn Human Design, the profile lines are an essential aspect of a person's Human Design chart.\n[...]\nThe profile lines are derived from the positions of the two most prominent conscious personality and unconscious design energies in a person's chart. These energies are represented by two numbers between 1 and 6, separated by a dash - with a total of 12 possible combinations.(1/3 – 1/4 – 2/4 – 2/5 – 3/5 – 3/6 – 4/1 – 4/6 – 5/1 – 5/2 – 6/2 – 6/3)\n[...]\nline and carries\n[...]\n. The first number in the profile\n[...]\n- while the second number\n[...]\nLINE 1 THE INVESTIGATOR 💭(1/3 – 1/4 – 4/1 – 5/1)\n[...]\nLINE 2 THE HERMIT 🐚(2/4 – 2/5 – 5/2 – 6/2)\n[...]\nLINE 3 THE MARTYR 🧪(3/5 – 3/6 – 1/3 – 6/3)\n[...]\nLINE 4 THE OPPORTUNIST 💌(4/1 – 4/6 – 1/4 – 2/4)\n[...]\nLINE 5 THE HERETIC 🛠️(5/1 – 5/2 – 2/5 – 3/5)\n[...]\nLINE 6 THE ROLE MODEL 🔮(6/2 – 6/3 – 3/6 – 4/6)\n[...]\nPerceived as disinterested and often experiencing radical shifts in life - the Line 6 goes through a unique 3-stage life process to emerge as a matured role model.Age 0-30: Lives life as a Line 3 without the natural resilience. Trial and error.Age 30-50: Withdraws to higher ground for perspective, goes to ‘sit on the roof’ and observe, analyse their experience and discover what is trustworthy & really works.Age 50+: Chiron return. Climbs down from the roof to engage with the world again, looked to for their unique wisdom.ADMINISTRATION, OPTIMISM, PEACEMAKER\n\n---\n\nTitle: Human Design Profile Lines 1–6 Explained: The Six Energetic Archetypes and How to Work With Them\nURL: https://annsmyth.com/blog/human-design-profile-lines-1-6\nPublished: 2025-07-26T13:46:33.000Z\nAuthor: Written By  Ann Smyth\nHighlights:\nHuman Design teaches us that we don’t just have a personality; we have an energetic architecture. Six ancient codes, woven into your nervous system, that shape how you trust, retreat, or rise under pressure. These are your Profile Lines, and they’re far more than numbers. They are codes made of two numbers, consciously and unconsciously expressed, that reflect the energetic posture you assume in this life. But before you try to understand what it means to be a 4/6, a 2/4, or a 5/1, you need to meet the parts individually. Because behind each profile are two lines, and behind those lines are archetypes. Energetic roles. Somatic patterns. Developmental strategies. These six profile lines are more than numbers. They are the quiet logic behind your preferences, your protection mechanisms, and your lived experience.\n[...]\n## Line 1 – The Investigator\n[...]\n5/1 Profile (Heretic/Investigator) – The Challenge\n[...]\nThe drive to be prepared\n[...]\n1)\n[...]\nfield (Line 5), making this profile both solution-oriented and self-\n[...]\nThe 5/1 often carries others’ expectations and uses research or strategy as a defence against being misread\n[...]\ntension here is managing\n[...]\nowning their powerful capacity to lead.\n[...]\n## Line 2 – The Hermit/Natural\n[...]\n6/2\n[...]\n## Line 3 – The Martyr/Experimenter\n[...]\n## Line 4 – The Opportunist/Connector\n[...]\n## Line 5 – The Heretic/Leader\n[...]\n## Line 6 – The Role Model/Visionary\n[...]\nthe first third of\n[...]\nlike Line\n[...]\ns, full of\n[...]\n, error, relationship rupt\n[...]\nthird (approx.\n[...]\n, regroup, and\n[...]\n. And in the final third (\n[...]\nChiron return, around age 50), they begin to embody the very wisdom they once sought from others.\n[...]\n## In Profile Combinations\n[...]\n3/6 Profile (Martyr/Role Model) – The Living Contrast This profile experiences life as contrast: the chaos of the 3 Line meets the high vantage of the 6. The early years are full of friction and growth; midlife offers perspective. The 3/6 learns not to run from their\n[...]\nstory but to alchemise it into embodied wisdom.\n[...]\n4/6 Profile (\n[...]\n) – The Regal\n[...]\n6/2 Profile (Role Model/Hermit) – The Exemplary Human This profile combines visionary presence with natural withdrawal. The 6/2 must protect its energy while stepping into visibility. The second line gives them an intuitive rhythm; the sixth asks them to embody what others have merely theorised.\n[...]\n6/3 Profile (Role Model/\n[...]\n) – The\n[...]\nurer One of the most\n[...]\nInvestigator/Mart\n[...]\nInvestigator/\n[...]\nHermit/Her\n[...]\n1 Profile (Heretic\n[...]\nRole Model/Martyr\n\n---\n\nTitle: Profiles in Human Design\nURL: https://www.humdes.com/en/kb/profiles/\nPublished: N/A\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\nStructurally, each Hexagram is a combination of six full and dashed lines, which are divided into two parts (Trigrams) and successively placed one above the other, like the floors of a residential building. The first three Lines (1,2,3) are called Personal and form the lower Trigram. The next three Lines (4,5,6) form the upper Trigram and are called Transpersonal.\n[...]\n| Line | Main Theme and Keywords Lines | Brief Description of the Line in the Profile |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Role Model | Transition. Wisdom, detachment, search for the ideal and perfection, being yourself. | If requested, he can share wisdom regarding this Hexagram (Gate). |\n[...]\n| Heretic | Universalisation. Saviour, paranoia, reputation, burning at the stake. | Looks for opportunities for universalization. Acts in a non-standard way, breaks stereotypes. |\n[...]\n| Opportunist | Externalization. Interaction, social networking, friendliness, convenience. | It spreads the possibilities of this energy in society, building a network of social connections. |\n[...]\n| Martyr | Adaptation. Trial and error, practicality, experiment, openness, materialism. | Gains practical experience with this energy, learns by trial and error. |\n[...]\n| Hermit | Projection. Modesty, talent, inherent closeness, naturalness. | Examines the energy potential of the Gate in seclusion, creates projections of this energy in the outer world. |\n[...]\n| Investigator | Introspection. Basis, self-absorption, fear, insecurity, empathy. | Explores the underlying potential and deeply reveals the fundamental basis of this energy. |\n[...]\nPersonal Profile people (1/3, 1/4, 2/4, 2/5, 3/5, 3/6, 4/6)\n[...]\n. They are self-centred and came to this\n[...]\n. Such people may\n[...]\n. If someone\n[...]\na person with a Personal Profile on their path,\n[...]\ndepends only on them\n[...]\n(5/1, 5/2, 6/2, 6/3\n[...]\nThe harmony of the Profile is determined by the harmonious or inharmonious combination of the Lines that form this Profile. Out of the twelve Profiles, six are harmonious (1/4, 4/1, 2/5, 5/2, 3/6, 6/3) and six more are inharmonious (1/3, 2/4, 3/5, 4/6, 5/1, 6/2). There is always tension between the Conscious and the Subconscious: the body does the opposite of what the Personality wants and expects.\n[...]\nProfile 1/3 Investigator — Martyr\n[...]\nProfile 1/4 Investigator — Opportunist\n[...]\nProfile 2/4 Hermit — Opportunist\n[...]\nProfile 2/5 Hermit — Heretic\n[...]\nProfile 3/5 Martyr — Heretic\n[...]\nProfile 3/6 Martyr — Role Model\n[...]\nProfile 4/1 Opportunist — Investigator\n[...]\nProfile 4/6 Opportunist — Role model\n[...]\nProfile 5/1 Heretic — Investigator\n[...]\nProfile 5/2 Heretic — Hermit\n[...]\nProfile 6/2 Role model — Hermit\n[...]\nProfile 6/3 Role Model — Martyr"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b1f43cf0-0b01-4fcb-be5a-abcfd9b49660","uuid":"bfadd86a-4f23-4b95-96db-586be59eaea7","timestamp":"2026-06-10T16:11:37.247Z","tool_use_result":[{"type":"text","text":"Title: Human Design Profile — The 12 Profiles and 6 Lines Explained - Human Design Hub\nURL: https://humandesignhub.app/en/library/profile-overview\nPublished: 2026-02-20T05:20:31.000Z\nAuthor: N/A\nHighlights:\n| Line | Name | Core Theme |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Line 1 | Investigator | Foundation, research, security through knowledge |\n| Line 2 | Hermit | Natural talent, withdrawal, the call from others |\n| Line 3 | Martyr | Trial and error, experiential learning, bonds made and broken |\n| Line 4 | Opportunist | Network, community, influence through relationships |\n| Line 5 | Heretic | Universalizing, projection field, practical solutions |\n| Line 6 | Role Model | Three life phases, observation, embodied wisdom |\n[...]\nLine 6— The Role Model lives in three distinct phases. In the first phase (roughly birth to early 30s), they live much like a Line 3, gathering experience and learning what works. In the second phase (30s–50s), they pull back to observe from a higher vantage point. In the third phase, they step back into the world as a genuine role model, embodying the wisdom they have accumulated.\n[...]\n| Profile | Nickname | Life Theme |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 1/3 | Investigating Martyr | Must build a solid knowledge base, then test it relentlessly through real-world experience. Life is a research project that never ends. |\n[...]\n| 1/4 | Investigating Opportunist | Deep foundation-building feeds directly into a close-knit network. Knowledge is meant to be shared with people who know and trust you. |\n[...]\n| 2/4 | Hermit Opportunist | Natural talent is discovered in solitude but reaches its fullness through community. The right community calls out gifts the 2/4 didn't know they had. |\n[...]\n| 2/5 | Hermit Heretic | Natural ability projected onto a mass scale. The 2/5 is often seen as a practical solver of collective problems. Alone time is essential to protect against projection overwhelm. |\n[...]\n| 3/\n[...]\n— and is often seen as a savior figure in the\n[...]\n| 3/6 | Experiential Role Model | The deepest trial-and-error Profile, eventually transforming into a living example. The three-phase arc of Line 6 is especially pronounced here: experiment, observe, embody. |\n[...]\n| 4/6 | Network Role Model | Influence through\n[...]\ncommunity, ultimately growing into a\n[...]\n| 5/1 | Heretical Investigator | Extraordinary reach and projection backed by genuinely deep knowledge. The 5/1 can be trusted to deliver because the research is always there. |\n[...]\n| 5/2 | Heretical Hermit |\n[...]\nmeets natural talent. The 5/2 is called by the world to\n[...]\nown yet.\n[...]\n| 6/2 | Role Model Hermit | Three life phases enriched by natural gifts that emerge in solitude. In the final phase, the 6/2 becomes a role model whose talents speak for themselves. |\n[...]\n| 6/3 | Role Model Martyr | Three life phases built on a foundation of rich experiential learning. The mistakes of the first phase become the wisdom of the third. |\n\n---\n\nTitle: HUMAN DESIGN: The 6 Profile Lines Explained // by Sarah Wilder | SARAHWILDER.CO\nURL: https://wildertalismans.com/blogs/human-des